<br>
This seems to be the general feeling of almost every player.  The thing is though...  EverQuest was never meant to be a high level game with a primary focus on raiding.  It was supposed to be a social dungeon game focused on small groups.   Raiding was created by the players and compensated for by the developers.  Today the entire game is based on raiding with 30 to 40 people.<br>
<br>
The closest anyone ever got to a raid in the first phase of the game was gathering a massive force to drop the only two dragons in the game.  Most of those people were from mixed guilds, and only the higher level members.  The panar zones were then added to the game as a diversion for more experienced players to keep playing.  The same can be said about Kedge.  At least until Kunark was released.<br>
<br>
After Kunark the larger guilds had something to do.  There were now dungeons offering compensation for large guilds hitting a target all at once.  There were more dragons.  There were key quests for a zone that was rumored to be the toughest in the game, and no CS would be offered in said zone.  After the release of Kunark EQ became more than a social game.  It became a guild based game.  What the developers lacked was the forsight to see that larger guilds would dominate and middle teir guilds would fight for scraps while lower teir guilds would stagnate.  Thus is the game we play now. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=193604" target=new><font size=5 face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color=darkred>Keelz Neversleep</font></a><BR><font size=2 face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif"><I>
